DSC-550 Final Project¶

Original Case Study - Youtube Trending Data.¶

Narrative With the COVID-19 pandemic, people around the U.S. have been forced to stay at home. In my case, I have many things to occupy myself with: Work (from home), school, family (just because they are away doesn't mean they get to go away) and, time permitting, the occasional on-line gathering with friends to play a session of Dungeons and Dragons. But what about other people?

An initial inspection of the dataframe reveals the following details:

  • trending_date and publish_time are not in date-time format.
  • category_id is only a number. The category labels can be found in the US_category_id.json file.

We need to import this data and merge it together.

data_r2 = pd.merge(data, cat_df, on='category_id', how='left')

Next, converting the trending_date and publish_time to datetime. Starting with trending_date, we notice that the format is an object that represents YY.DD.MM so we'll need to perform a couple of operations on this to get the datetime. With publish_time, we can split the time and date respectively.

In [9]:
# Convert from object to string.
data_r2['trending_date'] = data_r2['trending_date'].astype(str)

# Split the Year, Month and Date into separate columns,
data_r2[['Year','Date','Month']] = data_r2.trending_date.str.split(".",expand=True) 

# Convert Year, Month and Date into an integer
data_r2['Year'] = data_r2['Year'].astype(int)
data_r2['Date'] = data_r2['Date'].astype(int)
data_r2['Month'] = data_r2['Month'].astype(int)

# Add 2000 to the year
data_r2['Year'] = 2000 + data_r2['Year']

# Convert the the int year, month and date into a string.
data_r2['trending_date_int']= (data_r2['Year']* 10000 + data_r2['Month']* 100 +data_r2['Date'])

# Convert the the int year, month and date into a string and apply the the pandas datetime transformation
data_r2['trending_date_r'] = pd.to_datetime((data_r2['Year']* 10000 + data_r2['Month']* 100 +data_r2['Date']).astype(str),format='%Y%m%d')

# Split date and time from 
data_r2[['publish_date','publish_time_r']] = data_r2.publish_time.str.split("T",expand=True) 

# Convert the publish_date into datetime format. 
data_r2['publish_date_r'] = pd.to_datetime((data_r2['publish_date']).astype(str),format='%Y-%m-%d')

Next - Create some derived variables that help us to gauge the overall sentiment of these videos as well as how fast they are trending - We do that as follows:

In [10]:
# Function that subtracts the number of likes against dislikes, if the value is positive then returns a 1, else returns a 0.
def video_sentiment(row):
    result = row['likes'] - row['dislikes']
    if result > 0:
        value = 1
    else:
        value = 0
    return value
In [11]:
# Apply the function to return the positive sentiment.
data_r2['isPositive'] = data_r2.apply(video_sentiment, axis=1)

# Get the number of days between publish date and trending date:
data_r2['days_toTrend'] = (data_r2['trending_date_r'] - data_r2['publish_date_r']) / np.timedelta64(1, 'D')

Creating a Feature for Training

One question that arose as I was working with this dataset - What is the trending performance on each individual video? To elaborate: How can I tell if one video in particular fared better against the rest of the videos in this data set? In this case, we are going to gauge performance by comparing the total number of log views against the log views average. However, simply subtracting against the total average would not create an accurate representation, so for the purposes of this exercise we will use the average log view by category.

# Save the resulting group by as a dataframe and set the category as the default index

# Merge the dataframes 
data_r3 = pd.merge(data_r2, log_views_bycat, on='category', how='left')

# Compare the means of log vies against the log_views
data_r3['views_log_comp'] = data_r3['views_log1p'] - data_r3['views_log1p_mean']

# Histogram to view the distribution of video performance.
n, bins, patches = plt.hist(x=data_r3['views_log_comp'], bins='auto', color='#0504aa',
                            alpha=0.7, rwidth=0.85)

plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=45)
plt.title('Video Performance', fontsize=45)
plt.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=30)
In [35]:
# Function that labels video performance by the resulting mean comparison. If the resulting value is 0 or less, it means that the views are below the mean value
# Thus labelled as a bad performer in this dataset. For any values above 0, that means the video performed better than the rest of the group.
def trend_performance(row):
    if row['views_log_comp'] < 0:
        value = 0
    else:
        value = 1
    return value

words = []
classes = []
documents = []
ignore_words = ['?']
# loop through each sentence in our training data
for pattern in dict_fcm:
    # tokenize each word in the sentence
    w = nltk.word_tokenize(pattern['txt'])
    # add to our words list
    words.extend(w)
    # add to documents in our corpus
    documents.append((w, pattern['cat']))
    # add to our classes list
    if pattern['cat'] not in classes:
        classes.append(pattern['cat'])

# stem and lower each word and remove duplicates
words = [stemmer.stem(w.lower()) for w in words if w not in ignore_words]
words = list(set(words))

# remove duplicates

# create our training data
training = []
output = []
# create an empty array for our output
output_empty = [0] * len(classes)

# training set, bag of words for each sentence
for doc in documents:
    # initialize our bag of words
    bag = []
    # list of tokenized words for the pattern
    pattern_words = doc[0]
    # stem each word
    pattern_words = [stemmer.stem(word.lower()) for word in pattern_words]
    # create our bag of words array
    for w in words:
        bag.append(1) if w in pattern_words else bag.append(0)

    training.append(bag)
    # output is a '0' for each tag and '1' for current tag
    output_row = list(output_empty)
    output_row[classes.index(doc[1])] = 1
    output.append(output_row)

Conclusions

Going back to the article that prompted this research and comparing it to this data, it appears that there are no significant changes to video watching patterns: Entertainment and Music remain the top watched video categories. Some of the data transformations I did may appear unecessary. For example, I did not do anything with the publish date or trending date. However, we can use the dates to calculate a Rolling Moving Average numbers over time and use these for further analysis.

Applying PCA on the test data for the logistic regression had the effect of dropping the accuracy of the model by 9% or so. The trade-off here is that the ROC-AUC graph now looks like an actual curve and not a straight line. I chose not to apply PCA on the Random Forest Classifier data as a means to compare what was going on: We have a high-accuracy model but the ROC-AUC is so close to 1 that it these look more like a straight-line than a curve. The use of tag data to predict video category proved to be an interesting experiment that yielded some exciting results. While the high accuracy is questionable, it just provides encouragement to continue to test with the tags to see if we can identify other forms of trends and whatnot.
